[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    205[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mLocation:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m "The Honest Take" section ("the most valuable feature-engineering work was in the 'is the patient on an oncology protocol?' context flag. Without it, the general anomaly detector was flagging chemotherapy doses constantly, because chemotherapy doses are genuinely wildly out of normal ranges. The fix was not more sophisticated modeling. It was a reliable 'this patient is on a chemo protocol, suppress general dose anomalies for drugs in the active protocol' context flag. Plumbing that context through added more value than any model improvement we tried."); "Where it Struggles" Oncology bullet ("A chemotherapy-aware detection path is required; the general detector should suppress or re-contextualize alerts for patients on active oncology protocols").[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    206[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The Honest Take section identifies the oncology-protocol context flag as the most valuable feature-engineering work in the entire recipe, more valuable than any model improvement. The "Where it Struggles" section says a chemotherapy-aware detection path is required. The recipe's Patient Context That Has to Travel With the Dispense subsection lists "Encounter type and goals of care" as one of the minimum context fields ("A chemotherapy dose that would be wildly inappropriate in most contexts is correct in oncology. Palliative-care patients get doses that look anomalous relative to standard pain management because the clinical goals are different"). But the architectural artifacts that make the oncology / palliative-care context flag binding rather than aspirational are not specified anywhere in the General Architecture Pattern, the AWS Implementation, or the pseudocode walkthrough:[K
