[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    240[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m3[38;2;191;97;106m.[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mThe right severity tier for cross-reactivity alerts depends on the specific drug pair and the allergic-reaction history.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Penicillin-allergic patients with documented anaphylaxis getting first-generation cephalosporins might warrant interrupt-severity (because anaphylaxis is the high-stakes case). Penicillin-allergic patients with documented "rash-only" or unspecified reactions getting third-generation cephalosporins should generally not be interrupt-severity (the cross-reactivity rate is [38;2;191;97;106m<[38;2;191;97;106m1% and the clinical alternative is a fluoroquinolone or vancomycin, both of which have their own significant risks). The "almost always interrupt" framing collapses this clinical nuance into a single severity tier.[K
