[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    280[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mThis is LOW because the architectural intent is clear from context (diversion alerts go to a separate workflow than clinical alerts) and the consequence of getting it wrong is minor (alerts route to the wrong queue but are still surfaced). But the inconsistency between the prose-defined severity hierarchy, the pseudocode's severity comparison logic, and the sample-output's actual severity values is the kind of teaching-fidelity gap that erodes reader trust.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    281[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mFix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Either (a) add "investigation" as a fourth tier in the General Architecture Pattern Severity Tiering subsection, with an explicit definition ("'Investigation' is reserved for diversion-pattern alerts that route to the diversion investigation team rather than to the pharmacist's queue; it is parallel to the clinical severity tiers and is sorted separately"), or (b) introduce a separate "alert_class" field that distinguishes "clinical" (interrupt/synchronous/background) from "diversion" (investigation), and update the sample output to use both fields. Option (a) is the smaller editorial change; option (b) is the architecturally cleaner factoring.[K
