[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    287[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mLocation:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Expected Results "Sample interrupt-severity alert for a pediatric dose anomaly" (rule "MAX_DOSE_PER_KG_AMOXICILLIN_PEDIATRIC", actual 35.7, threshold 15.0, message "Standard pediatric amoxicillin dose for this age and weight is approximately 200-225 mg per dose"); Expected Results sample's narrative_summary ("a likely intent is 200-250 mg per dose three times daily").[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    288[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The 15 mg/kg-per-dose threshold and the recommended 200-225 mg-per-dose narrative reflect standard-dose AOM amoxicillin (40-50 mg/kg/day divided TID, which works out to ~13-17 mg/kg per dose). Current American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) clinical practice guidelines for acute otitis media recommend high-dose amoxicillin (80-90 mg/kg/day divided BID, which is 40-45 mg/kg per dose), driven by the prevalence of penicillin-non-susceptible pneumococcus. For pediatric pneumonia and UTI the standard dose is appropriate; for AOM the high dose is current guidance.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    289[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    290[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mThe sample's [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mprofile[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m field encodes [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mindication_otitis_media[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, which is exactly the indication where the 15 mg/kg threshold and the 200-225 mg recommendation are inconsistent with current AAP guidance. The 35.7 mg/kg dose that the alert flags is genuinely close to the high-dose-AOM target (40-45 mg/kg per dose), so the alert may be flagging a clinically appropriate high-dose-AOM order as anomalous.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    291[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    292[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mThis is LOW because (a) the sample is illustrative and not a clinical-decision-making artifact, (b) the recipe correctly addresses indication-aware dosing in the prose ("The drug's standard mg/kg/day dose by indication (otitis media vs. pneumonia vs. UTI)"), and (c) any production deployment will use a real drug-knowledge-base reference rather than this hard-coded threshold. But the inconsistency between the recipe's prose discipline (indication-aware) and the recipe's sample (indication-blind) is a minor teaching-fidelity gap, and the specific direction of the inconsistency (over-flagging high-dose AOM as anomalous) lines up with one of the bias surfaces the recipe identifies in The Honest Take ("a system trained on majority-population dosing patterns may flag as anomalous the legitimate dosing patterns").[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    293[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mFix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Update the sample alert to use indication-appropriate thresholds. Either (a) change the sample's indication to one where the 15 mg/kg-per-dose threshold is current (pneumonia or UTI) and update the narrative-summary recommended dose accordingly, or (b) keep the AOM indication and update the threshold to ~40 mg/kg per dose with a higher actual value (perhaps 70 mg/kg per dose for a more dramatic flag), with a narrative-summary recommending the AAP high-dose-AOM target of 80-90 mg/kg/day BID. Option (a) is the smaller editorial change; option (b) preserves the AOM context and aligns with current AAP guidance.[K
