[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    348[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;143;161;179m####[38;2;192;197;206m [38;2;143;161;179mWhat's Done Well[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    349[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    350[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe Saturday-night vignette is publication-ready voice. "Picture the same order in a 600-bed academic hospital at 3:15 a.m. Different pharmacist. Different workflow. The order comes through the CPOE into the pharmacy queue with all the usual formatting. The computerized decision support fired a weight-based dosing alert, but it also fires a weight-based dosing alert on roughly 40% of vancomycin orders because the reference range it uses is narrower than clinical practice. The pharmacist, eleven hours into a twelve-hour shift, processes the alert the way the other dozen she's seen tonight got processed: acknowledge and proceed. The dose dispenses. The patient's creatinine climbs over the next thirty-six hours. By the time the kidney injury is noticed, the patient is on dialysis consult." The contrast between the community-hospital save (the pharmacist's mental math catching the error) and the academic-hospital miss (the same pharmacist with the same training in a different alert-saturation environment) is the densest alert-fatigue framing in the cookbook to date.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    351[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The seven concrete texture examples (pediatric amoxicillin overdose with weight-field gap, the 83-year-old on triple anticoagulation with recent GI bleed, the ICU insulin trajectory drifting from 2 to 14 U/hr signaling sepsis, the post-op morphine pattern that's inconsistent with pain trajectory, the pharmacy technician with seven of twelve restock discrepancies, the home-delivery refill pattern escalating from 90/60 days to 45 days to 30 days, the controlled-substance pull pattern across user-station-drug-patient graphs) each map to a real medication-safety failure mode that any pharmacy informatics director would recognize. The clinical reasoning is correct in each case, the medications and routes are correctly named, and the pattern-vs-event distinction is exactly the architectural reframe the recipe is building toward.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    352[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The five-flavors-of-anomaly framing (dose, frequency-and-duration, interaction, controlled-substance pattern, aggregate-and-trend) is the right teaching anchor. Each flavor gets a one-paragraph treatment with structurally different data, model, and workflow requirements. The recipe explicitly says "A mature dispensing anomaly system handles all five. A useful first version picks one or two classes, does them well, and earns the right to expand," which is the operationally correct prioritization.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    353[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The reference-data subsection is unusually substantive. First Databank, Wolters Kluwer, Micromedex, Lexicomp, and Medi-Span are all named (real commercial drug knowledge bases). The open-source path through RxNorm, DailyMed, and OpenFDA is named with the right caveat ("None of them are a clean substitute for the commercial content because the commercial vendors spend enormous effort on the operational reference data ... For serious work you almost always end up licensing a commercial content feed. Budget for it early"). The version-tracking discipline ("drug knowledge bases change weekly. Store the version of the knowledge base used at the time of each alert") is the audit-trail discipline most production systems get wrong.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    354[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The patient-context subsection is publication-ready. The seven minimum context fields (demographics with age-banded windows, problem list with onset dates, complete active medication list including home meds reconciled at admission, recent labs including renal/hepatic/INR/electrolytes, allergies with normalization, location and acuity, encounter type and goals of care) are exactly the right minimum bar. The staleness framing ("a 30-day-old weight on an ICU patient is useless") and the EHR-integration framing ("The cache staleness is a design parameter: a 5-minute refresh is fine for chronic medications, not fine for an ICU patient whose potassium just came back critical") are the kind of detail-level teaching that distinguishes the cookbook.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    355[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The clinical-baselines-vs-statistical-baselines hybrid framing ("The hybrid approach (patient-level baseline where available, population-level fallback, clinical rules as hard-stop backstops) is what production systems tend to converge on") is the architecturally correct factoring and is explicit about the operational complexity ("now have three signal families to calibrate and three sources of alerts to route").[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    356[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The statistical-methods progression (rule-based → z-scores → CUSUM/EWMA → Isolation Forest → supervised classifiers → LLM clinical reasoning → graph analytics) is the right pedagogical order. The closing paragraph ("A reasonable technical progression: start with rule-based clinical screening over clean reference data, add population-level z-scores for high-volume drugs, add patient-trajectory CUSUM for continuously-dosed drugs, add Isolation Forest for multivariate patterns, add supervised re-ranking once you have labels, add graph analytics for controlled substances. Don't skip the rules layer in favor of starting with ML") is operationally correct and is the same defensive posture the cookbook has settled on for clinical-decision-support work.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    357[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The alert-fatigue subsection is the most substantive treatment of this constraint in the cookbook so far. The four practical consequences (every new model passes the alert-volume test, severity tiering is not optional, override tracking is part of the detection system, alert presentation matters) are concrete and operationally actionable. The closing posture ("Treat alert fatigue as a primary design constraint. It's not a UX concern. It's a patient safety concern, because the clinician who's been trained to ignore the system is less safe than they'd be with no system at all") is publication-ready voice on the most consequential clinical-informatics failure mode.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    358[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The Honest Take is publication-ready and should be preserved verbatim. The seven lessons (rules layer is not a stepping stone, alert fatigue math is harsher than you think, patient-context cache is the real hard part, diversion detection is politically sensitive, trajectory detection pays off in unexpected ways, oncology context flag was the most valuable feature engineering, explainability work should drive modeling choices) land the right teaching priorities. The closing trap warning ("do not let the business case be 'reduce adverse drug events by X%' ... Frame it as clinician-endorsed utility, and the metrics align with the clinical goal") is the kind of operations-engineer voice the cookbook is built on.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    359[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m Variations and Extensions covers the right adjacent patterns at the right depth (BCMA integration, outpatient and specialty pharmacy, medication reconciliation assist, PDMP integration, patient outreach, LLM-assisted triage, closed-loop TPN/compounding, time-of-day shift patterns for diversion). Each is one to two paragraphs with enough scope to start a conversation but not so much that it crowds the main recipe.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    360[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m Zero em dashes (direct U+2014 character check across the file: zero matches). No marketing language. No documentation-voice. The 70/30 vendor balance is preserved cleanly: the conceptual sections (Problem, Technology, General Architecture Pattern) are vendor-neutral and a reader on GCP or Azure could substitute their cloud's primitives without rewriting any of the teaching; AWS service names enter at the AWS Implementation section and stay there.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    361[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m HTML-comment TODO discipline is correct: eight TODOs total, all forward-placeholder for industry-source citation (alert override rates literature, ADE cost estimates from AHRQ/ISMP/IHI, FDA CDS guidance reference, validated LLM clinical-reasoning patterns), aws-samples and AWS blog post verification, and forward-looking Bedrock pattern emergence. No bracket-style visible TODOs that would render in published output.[K
