[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    398[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mLocation:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Expected Results "Sample diversion-pattern alert" [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140m"note"[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m field: "Pattern matches indicators published in the ASHP guidelines for controlled substance diversion; does not constitute proof of diversion. Investigation to be conducted under existing pharmacy-compliance protocol."[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    399[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The note field is correctly framed (the alert is a pattern, not an accusation; investigation responsibility lies with pharmacy-compliance, not the model output) and the ASHP reference is real (the ASHP "Guidelines on Preventing Diversion of Controlled Substances" is a published reference). The phrase "matches indicators published in the ASHP guidelines" is slightly stronger than what most production diversion detectors actually claim; production systems typically derive their patterns from a combination of ASHP guidance, NABP (National Association of Boards of Pharmacy) recommendations, internal investigation outcomes, and published research. The note as-written implies a tighter coupling between the model's specific signals and ASHP's specific indicators than may be warranted.[K
