[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    408[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mPattern: A1 (outcome-event idempotency) is the now-recurring trigger-idempotency finding, surfacing for the tenth consecutive recipe (2.4-2.10, 3.1, 3.2, 3.3, 3.4).[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m Same fix template (deterministic event-key derivation, conditional-write enforcement at the orchestration layer), different specific event source. The patient-safety stakes of Recipe 3.4 elevate the consequence: doubled override counts directly distort which rules look high-override and get retired, and a rule retired because of artificially-doubled counts can produce a missed-future-flag that is a missed-future-ADE. With this finding now flagged across ten consecutive recipes, the per-recipe-edit posture is producing diminishing returns. The cookbook editor should treat the trigger-idempotency appendix as the highest-leverage cookbook-wide editorial investment.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    409[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    410[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mPattern: A2 (DLQ / poison-message handling) is operationally critical for this recipe specifically because of the patient-safety stakes.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m For Recipes 3.1, 3.2, and 3.3 a dropped event is an operational concern (a missed flag, a missed label-row); for Recipe 3.4 a dropped event in the real-time-anomaly-service path is a dispense without a check, which is precisely the failure mode the entire pipeline is designed to prevent. The DLQ-depth alarm threshold for the real-time path should be 1 (single-event sensitivity), not the typical "alert on sustained backlog" pattern. The recipe's prose elsewhere (Why This Isn't Production-Ready, graceful-degradation paragraph) addresses the right discipline but at a different abstraction level (degraded-mode operation rather than per-event poison-message recovery).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    411[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    412[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mPattern: A3 (oncology / palliative-care context flag) is the most-consequential teaching gap in the recipe[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m because The Honest Take section identifies this as the single highest-value feature-engineering work in the entire recipe ("Plumbing that context through added more value than any model improvement we tried"). The recipe's pseudocode walkthrough doesn't reflect this lesson, so a reader who treats the pseudocode as the implementation specification builds a system that flags chemotherapy doses constantly (the failure mode the Honest Take warns against). The fix is editorially small (a paragraph in the General Architecture Pattern, a field in the Step 2 cache schema, a suppression check in the Step 3 rule-screen) but materially important because the recipe's domain authority depends on the pseudocode actually demonstrating the lessons in the prose. This is the same prose-vs-pseudocode asymmetry that surfaced in Recipes 3.1 and 3.3, but with a higher-stakes specific lesson.[K
