[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    414[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mPattern: A4 (cross-reactive allergy default severity) is a domain-accuracy concern with patient-safety implications in the opposite direction from a typical anomaly-detection finding.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m Most domain-accuracy findings in this recipe family are about under-detecting; this one is about over-restricting. Beta-lactam over-restriction in penicillin-allergic patients is a documented patient-safety problem with worse infection outcomes, longer stays, more C. difficile, and higher mortality. The recipe's "almost always interrupt-severity" comment in the canonical pseudocode is exactly the framing that drives over-restrictive rule libraries. The fix is editorially small (a per-pair severity calibration in the rule schema) but materially important because the cookbook's prescriptive voice means readers will copy the pseudocode framing into their rule libraries.[K
